blog.name: aziraphalesscrowley
blog.title: angel
blog.description: charlie | it's ineffable babey | send me writing prompts | AO3 is wordcountenthusiast

summary: hey idk if ur doing the a/c prompts still but i’ve been in That Mood so how about pride? (if u still want to of course)
question: hey idk if ur doing the a/c prompts still but i’ve been in That Mood so how about pride? (if u still want to of course)
answer:
Anon I’d literally die for you thank you so much for the request. And also, unless I explicitly say that I’m not, I’m always open to requests to feel free to send them in at any time, and I’ll get to them when I can. This turned out to be a bit more of self-worth than pride but I hope it works anyway.

                                                         — 

Crowley and Aziraphale loved to spend time in bed together. Not necessarily sleeping or doing anything of a sexual nature, but just relaxing together in quiet intimacy, enjoying the comfort of each other’s presence. Aziraphale typically read, and Crowley would lay there with him, or watch TV, or even just talk. Crowley talking didn’t always lead to a conversation, however, but Aziraphale loved to hear his voice, and never particularly minded his ramblings.

However, occasionally Aziraphale did respond to Crowley. And the conversations they had in their bed were typically very profound and left both of them with a sense of love for the other that deepened and expanded over time, like a river wearing away at a canyon.

This was one of those evenings.

Aziraphale was reading, not one of his dusty old tomes that typically resided in the book store, but something that appeared to be a murder mystery from where Crowley lay at the end of the bed, staring at the ceiling.

“What do you think it would have been like, angel?”

“Hmm?” Aziraphale responded, not knowing fully what Crowley meant.

“If we hadn’t stopped the apocalypse, I mean. Humanity would be gone, of course, but what would it mean for us?”

“Well, I imagine that we wouldn’t be able to spend much time together.”

Crowley snorted. 

“Well, of course. As you so eloquently put it, your side wouldn’t like that very much.”

“And, I presume, that Gabriel wouldn’t be particularly happy with me…” Aziraphale didn’t like to think about Gabriel very much. The Archangel had caused a lot of problems for him and had hurt him for a long time, but being around Crowley dulled the ache a bit. It allowed him to forget about the teasing smirks that Gabriel had given as he tore away everything Aziraphale was proud of and attempted to strip him of his lighthearted and loving personality. 

Aziraphale didn’t like spending time in Heaven. He avoided it at all costs, actually, and Crowley knew that it was a rather touchy subject.

“Aziraphale, I know you hate to talk about it, but what did he… do to you? You don’t hate anyone, except him. You hate him so much.”

Aziraphale reached out to Crowley, knowing that he wouldn’t fully be able to tell the demon without some measure of support. Crowley responded by crawling towards the head of the bed and laying next to Aziraphale, gently holding one of his hands and laying his head on Aziraphale’s shoulder. As the angel began to speak, he was comforted by the gentle vibrations that ran through his body.

“He was hateful, dear, but it was always more than that. He was the type that made me question if being kind was Angelic or quite the opposite. His cruelty was casual and relentless, and he never passed up a chance to tear me down. And it wasn’t only my actions, it was my personality. My soul. Even my corporeal form, if he got the chance.”

Crowley squeezed his hand tightly but didn’t talk. The silence lasted a minute or two, and just when Aziraphale was about to ask him what he was thinking, he spoke.

“I’m sorry, angel. He hurt you. And I wish I could help you. But damaged self-image takes a while to heal. Especially if it’s the only thing you’ve known. I’m here for you.”

Aziraphale wanted to say a lot to that. He wanted to say that every time he heard Gabriel’s voice, or even thought about it, his heart rate picked up and he felt nervous. He wanted to say that he did believe that he was useless. That he was awkward. That he was stupid and hopeless. That he would never accomplish anything.

But instead, he looked over to Crowley, who was staring at him with tender eyes.

“I love you, dear.”

“I love you too, angel.”

He wanted to say that he did believe that he was useless. That he was awkward. That he was stupid and hopeless. That he would never accomplish anything.

But instead, he looked over to Crowley, who was staring at him with tender eyes.

“I love you, dear.”

“I love you too, angel.”

Crowley and Aziraphale loved to spend time in bed together. Not necessarily sleeping or doing anything of a sexual nature, but just relaxing together in quiet intimacy, enjoying the comfort of each other’s presence. Aziraphale typically read, and Crowley would lay there with him, or watch TV, or even just talk. Crowley talking didn’t always lead to a conversation, however, but Aziraphale loved to hear his voice, and never particularly minded his ramblings.

However, occasionally Aziraphale did respond to Crowley. And the conversations they had in their bed were typically very profound and left both of them with a sense of love for the other that deepened and expanded over time, like a river wearing away at a canyon.

This was one of those evenings.

Aziraphale was reading, not one of his dusty old tomes that typically resided in the book store, but something that appeared to be a murder mystery from where Crowley lay at the end of the bed, staring at the ceiling.

“What do you think it would have been like, angel?”

“Hmm?” Aziraphale responded, not knowing fully what Crowley meant.

“If we hadn’t stopped the apocalypse, I mean. Humanity would be gone, of course, but what would it mean for us?”

“Well, I imagine that we wouldn’t be able to spend much time together.”

Crowley snorted. 

“Well, of course. As you so eloquently put it, your side wouldn’t like that very much.”

“And, I presume, that Gabriel wouldn’t be particularly happy with me…” Aziraphale didn’t like to think about Gabriel very much. The Archangel had caused a lot of problems for him and had hurt him for a long time, but being around Crowley dulled the ache a bit. It allowed him to forget about the teasing smirks that Gabriel had given as he tore away everything Aziraphale was proud of and attempted to strip him of his lighthearted and loving personality. 

Aziraphale didn’t like spending time in Heaven. He avoided it at all costs, actually, and Crowley knew that it was a rather touchy subject.

“Aziraphale, I know you hate to talk about it, but what did he… do to you? You don’t hate anyone, except him. You hate him so much.”

Aziraphale reached out to Crowley, knowing that he wouldn’t fully be able to tell the demon without some measure of support. Crowley responded by crawling towards the head of the bed and laying next to Aziraphale, gently holding one of his hands and laying his head on Aziraphale’s shoulder. As the angel began to speak, he was comforted by the gentle vibrations that ran through his body.

“He was hateful, dear, but it was always more than that. He was the type that made me question if being kind was Angelic or quite the opposite. His cruelty was casual and relentless, and he never passed up a chance to tear me down. And it wasn’t only my actions, it was my personality. My soul. Even my corporeal form, if he got the chance.”

Crowley squeezed his hand tightly but didn’t talk. The silence lasted a minute or two, and just when Aziraphale was about to ask him what he was thinking, he spoke.

“I’m sorry, angel. He hurt you. And I wish I could help you. But damaged self-image takes a while to heal. Especially if it’s the only thing you’ve known. I’m here for you.”

Aziraphale wanted to say a lot to that. He wanted to say that every time he heard Gabriel’s voice, or even thought about it, his heart rate picked up and he felt nervous. He wanted to say that he did believe that he was useless. That he was awkward. That he was stupid and hopeless. That he would never accomplish anything.

But instead, he looked over to Crowley, who was staring at him with tender eyes.

“I love you, dear.”

“I love you too, angel.”
